<div id="review_2146948206" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2146948206" />
    <a title="Kalin" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/741149-kalin"><img alt="Kalin" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1502630193p2/741149.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2146948206?book_show_action=true">Nov 09, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kalin" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kalin" href="/user/show/741149-kalin">Kalin</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="ebook 9780393246193" href="/book/show/26889508-are-we-smart-enough-to-know-how-smart-animals-are">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/741149-kalin?shelf=reviewed-in-english">reviewed-in-english</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2146948206" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7151973701676761464">This book is too rich and diverse to sum up in a single paragraph, but if there&apos;s one lesson I will take from it, it is: For animals and humans, cognitive abilities run along a scale. It is never a case of &quot;we have this, and animals don&apos;t&quot;; it is &quot;species X has this to the extent Y--as far as we can tell from our current observations.&quot; That in itself is a giant step toward humanity&apos;s next, more caring, more empathetic version.<br/><br/>A few favorite passages:<br/><br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://choveshkata.net/forum/viewtopic.php?p=32029#p32029'>https://choveshkata.net/forum/viewtop...</a></span>
  <span id="freeText7151973701676761464" style="display:none">This book is too rich and diverse to sum up in a single paragraph, but if there's one lesson I will take from it, it is: For animals and humans, cognitive abilities run along a scale. It is never a case of "we have this, and animals don't"; it is "species X has this to the extent Y--as far as we can tell from our current observations." That in itself is a giant step toward humanity's next, more caring, more empathetic version.<br /><br />A few favorite passages:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://choveshkata.net/forum/viewtopic.php?p=32029#p32029">https://choveshkata.net/forum/viewtop...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="7151973701676761464" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


